English Summary

Drama of the Dram and Rumble of the Ruble

The recent appreciation of the Armenian dram has caused some concern in the market. The analysis examines how the Armenian currencys exchange rate has been significantly influenced by the Russian rubles fluctuations, particularly in light of recent events including new US sanctions on Gazprombank, the EUs announcement about stopping Russian gas purchases, and end-of-year debt settlement patterns in Russia. These factors led to the rubles depreciation from 100 to 115 against the dollar in late November 2023, though it has since stabilized at around 99 rubles per dollar.

The Armenian drams value has experienced three major shocks since 2012: first during the 2014 Russian financial crisis, then during the 2020 Nagorno-Karabakh war, and most recently following the loss of Artsakh in 2023. While the drams recent appreciation makes it one of the strongest performing currencies among convertible currencies since 2022, this strength has negatively impacted Armenias export, tourism, and IT sectors. For instance, IT companies that received 4.8 million drams for $10,000 in 2022 now receive only 3.8 million drams for the same amount, representing a significant loss in local currency terms.
